title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:em><fr:strong>(binary) relation</fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> from a set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to a set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, written <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } B]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R\in  \mathrm {Rel}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R\subseteq  A\times  B]]></fr:tex>. We shall typically write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {R}b]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,b\right )\mathclose {}}\in  R]]></fr:tex>. More generally, a <fr:em><fr:strong>relation between multiple sets</fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A_i\right )\mathclose {}}_{i\in  I}]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a subset of the cartesian product <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod _{i\in  I} A_i]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>